WEBVTT
Kind: captions
Language: en

00:00:15.552 --> 00:00:17.900
﻿Plasma Youth Sports Games
with Unsuccess of the champion,

00:00:18.069 --> 00:00:20.410
would like to thank Slaven Bilić
for stepping in as the host.

00:00:20.544 --> 00:00:23.707
Bilić is one of the first sponsors,
ambassador and is our biggest promoter.

00:00:23.927 --> 00:00:27.200
He used his life and sports experience
in order to prepare high-quality content

00:00:27.560 --> 00:00:29.800
with his guests for all generations.
Thanks, Nane!

00:00:39.780 --> 00:00:43.100
When you look behind you,
what was your strong point?

00:00:43.660 --> 00:00:48.580
Apart from the serve and volley.
I don’t understand, I asked you that...

00:00:48.820 --> 00:00:55.300
How is it possible that your
favorite court is Wimbledon

00:00:55.580 --> 00:01:01.594
and that you are famous for it,
not just because you won?

00:01:03.060 --> 00:01:10.001
So, grass and London can’t be
more different from Split,

00:01:10.115 --> 00:01:12.515
since there are no
grass courts there.

00:01:12.648 --> 00:01:14.977
Unless you played on the
Poljud football stadium.

00:01:15.144 --> 00:01:17.508
In Split, you played on
clay or concrete courts.

00:01:17.798 --> 00:01:21.500
How come the grass courts
suited you more?

00:01:23.116 --> 00:01:26.695
It was love at first sight
when I first played on grass.

00:01:26.934 --> 00:01:30.899
I didn’t particularly enjoy
playing on that surface,

00:01:31.321 --> 00:01:37.188
but my style was suited to it.
And that immediately brought results.

00:01:39.742 --> 00:01:43.942
Another thing was that I could
always wear white clothes.

00:01:44.057 --> 00:01:46.617
They were clean, I could wear
the same socks for five days

00:01:46.896 --> 00:01:49.736
and didn’t have to wash
them from the dirt.

00:01:50.427 --> 00:01:54.820
Everything was soft, beautiful,
and smelled nice.

00:01:55.106 --> 00:01:58.890
There was complete order.
And I always had good results.

00:01:59.247 --> 00:02:01.664
Sometimes I would prepare
for Wimbledon at Lora's

00:02:01.762 --> 00:02:04.162
indoor court on a tartan surface.

00:02:05.920 --> 00:02:09.560
I slipped a few times there,
and the crowd laughed at me.

00:02:09.698 --> 00:02:12.138
And that’s when I got injured.

00:02:12.416 --> 00:02:19.330
That’s why many people wondered
how I could be so good,

00:02:19.565 --> 00:02:22.822
yet never train on grass courts.

00:02:25.627 --> 00:02:28.674
I just loved those grass courts.

00:02:28.930 --> 00:02:34.812
Otherwise, my style of playing...
I was the biggest "pimpler",

00:02:35.058 --> 00:02:38.705
which means someone who...
Since I grew up on clay,

00:02:39.009 --> 00:02:44.235
I never came to the net.
I would run for three days.

00:02:44.620 --> 00:02:50.180
When I turned professional,
my style changed 380 degrees.

00:02:51.660 --> 00:02:56.100
Serve and volley, aggressive play.

00:02:56.420 --> 00:03:00.980
And yet, sometimes I could adapt
to playing on clay courts,

00:03:01.260 --> 00:03:05.260
standing back, running, and if needed,
playing like that for three days.

00:03:06.298 --> 00:03:07.287
Incredible.

00:03:10.620 --> 00:03:16.460
We talked about this earlier,
but I don’t agree with that.

00:03:17.780 --> 00:03:22.220
They always said you had
trouble with mental preparation.

00:03:22.420 --> 00:03:28.580
Maybe if compared to Sampras or Borg,
but you were something else...

00:03:28.900 --> 00:03:31.460
If I were to compare you
to someone in football,

00:03:31.700 --> 00:03:33.900
for me, you'd be like
Gascoigne or Cassano.

00:03:34.100 --> 00:03:36.060
Do you know how long they'd
last in the world of tennis?

00:03:36.300 --> 00:03:38.220
One second.

00:03:38.700 --> 00:03:44.940
To me, you're a "monster"
because of your achievements.

00:03:45.180 --> 00:03:47.860
How did you prepare for matches?

00:03:48.060 --> 00:03:53.980
You and I have a mutual friend,
but he’s like a brother to me, Ivo Kuzzi.

00:03:54.180 --> 00:03:57.340
He was with you at the US Open.

00:03:57.540 --> 00:04:01.140
He told me about it earlier,
and we talked again days ago.

00:04:01.380 --> 00:04:05.660
What fascinated him about you
was your transformation.

00:04:05.900 --> 00:04:12.580
You played the US Open round of 16
on center court against Rafter.

00:04:13.460 --> 00:04:20.540
And in the morning, you and he
played small football in Central Park.

00:04:20.780 --> 00:04:27.540
You were focused on that game,
2determined to beat him.

00:04:27.780 --> 00:04:31.380
He played carefully
so he wouldn’t hurt you.

00:04:31.900 --> 00:04:35.980
You were completely
dedicated to that game.

00:04:36.180 --> 00:04:39.140
Then when you played cards,
you'd get upset and tear them.

00:04:39.340 --> 00:04:42.860
And then suddenly,
as if nothing had happened,

00:04:43.060 --> 00:04:46.100
you'd go to center court
in front of 20,000 people.

00:04:46.340 --> 00:04:52.820
Ivo told me Trump was there.
And you won. You switched.

00:04:53.340 --> 00:05:00.976
Things like that relaxed me.
I remember it was an evening match.

00:05:01.660 --> 00:05:08.320
If I woke up at eight in the morning
thinking about the match,

00:05:09.160 --> 00:05:13.882
I wouldn't have prepared well.

00:05:16.220 --> 00:05:21.940
We’d go to Central Park,
play football, play cards,

00:05:22.220 --> 00:05:25.580
and that filled me up.

00:05:26.180 --> 00:05:34.740
I took football very seriously.
I didn’t want to lose.

00:05:34.940 --> 00:05:38.340
And when we played cards,
I wanted to win even more.

00:05:38.580 --> 00:05:43.500
When we played Briškula and Trešet,
those were my rituals.

00:05:44.060 --> 00:05:55.446
That was it, until warm-up began.
Then, I focused only on the match.

00:05:58.395 --> 00:06:06.207
What I did earlier filled my day
and sharpened my focus.

00:06:06.597 --> 00:06:08.480
That’s just how it was.

00:06:09.124 --> 00:06:15.004
Even though I lost that match,
and Rafter won the US Open.

00:06:15.860 --> 00:06:21.860
That’s how I relaxed. -Yes.

00:06:22.420 --> 00:06:26.260
If you spent the whole day,
from eight in the morning

00:06:26.540 --> 00:06:30.620
until eight in the evening,
only thinking about the match,

00:06:30.820 --> 00:06:32.860
you’d lose energy.

00:06:33.140 --> 00:06:36.700
But those were big swings,
going from one extreme to another.

00:06:36.980 --> 00:06:40.180
We football players did that,
but it’s still a team sport.

00:06:40.420 --> 00:06:43.740
That’s something different,
but we’ll talk about that now.

00:06:43.940 --> 00:06:47.833
You are a great athlete.
You love all kinds of sports.

00:06:48.024 --> 00:06:52.528
You even trained football at Hajduk.
-Yes, I did. When you were the coach.

00:06:53.180 --> 00:06:57.380
Where did that come from?

00:06:57.620 --> 00:07:01.700
Just to say, it used to be normal,
and it’s not a bad message for kids.

00:07:01.940 --> 00:07:05.380
And this is a show for kids.
Of course, primarily for kids.

00:07:05.660 --> 00:07:10.860
It used to be normal for kids
to try at least two sports.

00:07:11.100 --> 00:07:13.980
Balić trained basketball
before switching to handball.

00:07:14.180 --> 00:07:17.900
Toni Kukoč trained football,
Štimac played handball,

00:07:18.060 --> 00:07:20.260
and I also trained swimming.

00:07:20.540 --> 00:07:24.700
Did you train football before,
or only in 2001 when I was coach?

00:07:25.380 --> 00:07:30.020
At first, I trained a little,
but then I had to decide.

00:07:30.260 --> 00:07:35.780
But in 1997, I had a few of
the best weeks of my life.

00:07:37.380 --> 00:07:41.060
I remember it was year-end,
and my arm was hurting.

00:07:41.260 --> 00:07:44.740
At that time, Hajduk allowed me
to train with the juniors.

00:07:44.980 --> 00:07:48.060
In the juniors then, there were
players like Pletikosa, Deranja,

00:07:48.300 --> 00:07:53.620
Miladin... That was the 1979
generation. -Šera, Sablja.

00:07:55.660 --> 00:07:59.860
During those weeks,
Ivo also joined me.

00:08:00.060 --> 00:08:04.940
Zoran Vulić was the coach,
and sometimes Ivić showed up.

00:08:05.180 --> 00:08:08.620
I even got advice from Ivić.

00:08:09.780 --> 00:08:15.100
I froze up because of him,
and also because of Vulić.

00:08:15.380 --> 00:08:17.380
I really enjoyed it.

00:08:17.620 --> 00:08:21.020
Those were some of the best
weeks of my life.

00:08:21.260 --> 00:08:29.986
I’d come to training, go to the
junior locker room for my things.

00:08:32.695 --> 00:08:34.630
That’s something unforgettable.

00:08:34.740 --> 00:08:38.980
Where does this Hajduk obsession
come from for everyone?

00:08:40.980 --> 00:08:45.180
Anyone born in Split
supports Hajduk.

00:08:45.420 --> 00:08:49.420
Hajduk is loved,
and people live for it.

00:08:49.660 --> 00:08:54.980
But I love football.
It might be my favorite sport.

00:08:55.260 --> 00:08:58.260
I might even love it
more than tennis.

00:08:58.500 --> 00:09:02.820
I’m not one of those people
who only watches the national team.

00:09:02.935 --> 00:09:06.274
I follow matches in the first,
second, and third leagues.

00:09:06.352 --> 00:09:08.636
I follow all our clubs
in international matches.

00:09:08.755 --> 00:09:11.496
Since your time,
and even now.

00:09:11.630 --> 00:09:13.230
I just love football.

00:09:14.822 --> 00:09:18.066
Now, when I trained with Novak,
he also loves football.

00:09:18.235 --> 00:09:23.715
He would often ask: "Goran,
where does this player play?"

00:09:23.907 --> 00:09:27.081
And I’d just answer him,
because I knew them all.

00:09:27.223 --> 00:09:29.463
I love football.

00:09:31.500 --> 00:09:36.140
You trained two clubs I love
the most, Hajduk and West Bromwich.

00:09:36.380 --> 00:09:41.980
I was also invited to West Bromwich.
I was on their field and in their locker room.

00:09:42.340 --> 00:09:50.780
When Roy Hodgson was the coach.
I love football, and I enjoy it.

00:09:50.966 --> 00:09:53.312
I love watching matches,
and I also love playing.

00:09:53.434 --> 00:09:56.000
Currently, I play less
because my knee hurts.

00:09:56.200 --> 00:10:02.187
It was something new for me,
being part of a team.

00:10:02.641 --> 00:10:09.383
Coming to training in the morning,
being part of something different.

00:10:09.561 --> 00:10:14.758
They even accepted me well.
Everyone accepted me.

00:10:16.100 --> 00:10:17.725
And truly...

00:10:19.366 --> 00:10:25.639
I had never played football before,
except in front of my house.

00:10:25.925 --> 00:10:32.420
I never had a coach tell me:
"Lean forward, position your body..."

00:10:32.636 --> 00:10:34.770
Like Vule, who was my coach.

00:10:37.247 --> 00:10:40.295
I started training,
becoming part of the team.

00:10:40.452 --> 00:10:43.193
I started learning how to
move the ball faster.

00:10:43.451 --> 00:10:49.608
How to cross the ball,
how to play with the team.

00:10:50.680 --> 00:10:58.112
Those days really stayed with me.
-When such giants...

00:10:58.784 --> 00:11:01.540
I’ll tell you a short story.

00:11:01.780 --> 00:11:04.180
It’s about Toni Kukoč,
who is your relative.

00:11:04.309 --> 00:11:06.856
Toni and I lived
in the same building.

00:11:06.979 --> 00:11:09.660
He lived on the first floor,
I lived on the fourth.

00:11:09.804 --> 00:11:13.160
I’m ten days older than him.
Our parents knew each other.

00:11:13.351 --> 00:11:16.121
I knew him well, but we
hadn’t seen each other in years.

00:11:16.283 --> 00:11:19.065
A few years ago,
Hajduk played Villarreal in qualifiers.

00:11:20.060 --> 00:11:24.340
I was with Leo,
and he was with his godfather.

00:11:24.620 --> 00:11:29.500
But I sat next to him. He was,
of course, wearing a Hajduk jersey.

00:11:29.820 --> 00:11:35.700
It was late July or early August.
Hajduk lost and didn’t go through.

00:11:36.020 --> 00:11:40.980
Villarreal was better.
At the end of the match,

00:11:41.340 --> 00:11:44.860
there was a special atmosphere
in the northern stand.

00:11:45.860 --> 00:11:50.620
While watching,
you could see tears in his eyes.

00:11:50.860 --> 00:11:52.860
And I heard him say:

00:11:53.140 --> 00:12:00.860
"Why did I never play here,
but 1.5 km away, up there?"

00:12:01.100 --> 00:12:03.660
I thought he was joking.

00:12:04.380 --> 00:12:09.540
He played with Jordan, was in Chicago,
was the best European player...

00:12:09.900 --> 00:12:13.460
And yet he said something like that.

00:12:13.700 --> 00:12:18.060
Or you, in 2001, when I was Hajduk’s coach.
That was my first coaching job.

00:12:18.340 --> 00:12:24.770
It was really possible to sign you
and have you play in the league.

00:12:24.980 --> 00:12:30.660
Because you won Wimbledon.
That impossible desire for Hajduk.

00:12:30.980 --> 00:12:34.268
I lived in Split in a building
known as the "Chinese Wall."

00:12:34.581 --> 00:12:43.461
First, I lived on... then we moved...
It’s simply in my blood.

00:12:44.820 --> 00:12:49.100
Maybe they injected something
into my blood when I was born.

00:12:49.380 --> 00:12:54.474
It doesn’t matter if you play
for Hajduk or just love it.

00:12:54.911 --> 00:12:58.468
It simply can’t be described.

00:12:58.820 --> 00:13:05.580
My six-year-old son supports Hajduk.

00:13:06.620 --> 00:13:13.500
I always tell him he can support Hajduk
only after we pass Sveti Rok.

00:13:14.540 --> 00:13:19.140
A few days ago, when we were in Split
at my grandparents' house, he said:

00:13:19.420 --> 00:13:26.780
"Dad, on every building here,
it says Hajduk or has graffiti with it.

00:13:27.100 --> 00:13:31.420
That doesn’t exist in Zagreb.
People here are much more relaxed."

00:13:32.860 --> 00:13:35.241
I told him Split is different.

00:13:35.429 --> 00:13:39.860
The atmosphere is different.
The love for the club is different.

00:13:40.140 --> 00:13:44.220
A six-year-old noticed that.

00:13:44.940 --> 00:13:49.416
On every building,
he saw the Hajduk crest.

00:13:50.740 --> 00:13:57.540
That’s just how we in Split are.
We’re not easy to deal with, but...

00:13:58.060 --> 00:14:03.460
I remember when Jugoplastika
won everything. Just like you.

00:14:03.660 --> 00:14:07.260
You were our role models.
We were proud of you.

00:14:07.701 --> 00:14:11.465
Even though we footballers
played well in Yugoslavia.

00:14:11.771 --> 00:14:17.114
We won the Yugoslav Cup,
but that can’t compare to you.

00:14:19.828 --> 00:14:22.770
You come from an individual sport...

00:14:23.580 --> 00:14:30.220
Somehow, we always had success
in individual sports.

00:14:30.500 --> 00:14:37.060
But here, people prefer team sports.

00:14:37.540 --> 00:14:41.700
Because in them, there’s chemistry,
energy, and tactics.

00:14:41.900 --> 00:14:49.780
Where the rule is that the team
is greater than the sum of its parts.

00:14:50.220 --> 00:14:54.660
But what’s interesting is that
both before and after...

00:14:54.860 --> 00:15:04.540
At one point, Croatia had three cases:
Kostelić's, Ivanišević, and Vlašić.

00:15:04.820 --> 00:15:06.940
In just a few years.

00:15:07.860 --> 00:15:12.140
Reaching the very top
in individual sports.

00:15:12.380 --> 00:15:18.260
And then Blanka, and later Nikola.
But Blanka, you, Janica, and Ivica...

00:15:18.700 --> 00:15:23.940
All these names
have one common factor.

00:15:24.380 --> 00:15:31.780
Incredible commitment,
dedication, and parental influence.

00:15:37.530 --> 00:15:40.811
Going back to a question...
What if your father Srđan

00:15:40.990 --> 00:15:43.367
and mother took you to an academy?

00:15:43.545 --> 00:15:49.985
Would you have succeeded?
-I think I would have.

00:15:54.046 --> 00:15:59.286
Because Srđan would
have come to see how I play.

00:15:59.419 --> 00:16:02.019
He would have come to check.

00:16:03.112 --> 00:16:07.632
He never really interfered with
the work of any coach I had.

00:16:08.262 --> 00:16:13.101
He would come to tournaments and watch
everything, but he didn't get involved.

00:16:13.316 --> 00:16:18.199
Thank God that I got to have many great
coaches and players around me back home.

00:16:18.410 --> 00:16:22.937
I was younger back then, so I kind of...
He never held me back. He was just...

00:16:23.067 --> 00:16:25.918
He was just hanging around.
-Exactly, he was around.

00:16:26.071 --> 00:16:30.262
And the only thing he would ever say
was: 'Nobody touches the serve.'

00:16:31.419 --> 00:16:36.845
And yes, in Split we've always been
known for team sports like football,

00:16:37.049 --> 00:16:42.641
with Jugoplastika and Hajduk. Then we
had those incredible water polo teams,

00:16:42.914 --> 00:16:48.747
Mornar, Jadran, and Pošk,
that were European champions...

00:16:49.591 --> 00:16:52.841
We've always had sailing, rowing,

00:16:53.115 --> 00:17:00.552
but also strong judokas,
wrestlers, boxers, and weightlifters.

00:17:01.493 --> 00:17:05.450
But it was always kind of collective.

00:17:06.860 --> 00:17:11.580
Even handball - look at
Pero Metličić and Ivano Balić...

00:17:11.900 --> 00:17:15.580
Of course, they're from there too...
Yes, absolutely.

00:17:17.060 --> 00:17:20.340
But in individual sports,
it's different.

00:17:20.580 --> 00:17:23.300
For example, I never liked anyone
watching me while I trained.

00:17:23.540 --> 00:17:27.220
I had my own crew, my own team,
and that's a whole different thing.

00:17:27.500 --> 00:17:30.620
In your sport, it's normal
to have people around.

00:17:30.900 --> 00:17:33.500
You can mention Steffi Graf's father,
or Monica Seles' dad, or Becker's,

00:17:33.740 --> 00:17:38.340
and then of course the Williams sisters,
Nadal's uncle, Djokovic's father...

00:17:38.740 --> 00:17:42.500
There's always someone who has to be
there to offer immense support.

00:17:42.740 --> 00:17:46.060
I think these are sports where you
must have your family's support.

00:17:46.260 --> 00:17:48.540
It's very hard to succeed if you don't.

00:17:48.740 --> 00:17:52.500
Someone from your family
has to be there,

00:17:53.460 --> 00:17:58.380
although they don't need to be
tennis players themselves.

00:17:58.620 --> 00:18:00.940
Take Nadal's uncle, for example,
the guy's a genius.

00:18:01.180 --> 00:18:04.620
You can tell it's a successful family.

00:18:04.900 --> 00:18:08.300
His brother played
sports at a high level.

00:18:09.420 --> 00:18:16.180
But Nadal is naturally right-handed. His
uncle made him switch hands somehow...

00:18:16.460 --> 00:18:21.460
And who knows if Nadal would've been
as good had he stayed right-handed?

00:18:21.629 --> 00:18:23.429
How can you know something like that?

00:18:23.579 --> 00:18:28.010
Those methods are often
right on the edge.

00:18:28.230 --> 00:18:31.063
On the edge of genius and madness.

00:18:32.340 --> 00:18:35.668
But he is a genius,
and he turned Nadal into one too.

00:18:36.268 --> 00:18:40.825
And imagine what kind of struggle
the kid had to go through? Right?

00:18:41.300 --> 00:18:47.660
I don't know how it all came about,
because he's completely right-handed.

00:18:49.020 --> 00:18:53.020
It's unbelievable
how his uncle saw that.

00:18:53.260 --> 00:18:58.625
And of course, there's the process
Đoković's father went through...

00:18:58.805 --> 00:19:01.485
With Federer, I'm not as familiar
with the background.

00:19:01.612 --> 00:19:03.874
But in every case, a parent
has to sacrifice something

00:19:03.974 --> 00:19:06.164
for their child to make it in sport.

00:19:06.536 --> 00:19:10.579
Look at the Kostelić family,
their story is in a league of its own.

00:19:10.739 --> 00:19:15.416
It's incredible. There's no snow
in Sljeme, and from there came

00:19:15.572 --> 00:19:20.446
the best female skier in the world
and the best male skier too.

00:19:20.790 --> 00:19:25.010
It's truly something else.
Then you have Blanka...

00:19:27.780 --> 00:19:32.860
Joško was a top-level decathlete...
-And her mom was a track athlete too...

00:19:33.199 --> 00:19:40.080
Yes, the whole family was into sports...
They created something unbelievable.

00:19:40.228 --> 00:19:43.165
Back when we were doing athletics,
it was just something...

00:19:43.348 --> 00:19:46.432
And then Blanka came along,
and it all changed.

00:19:46.586 --> 00:19:50.455
For me, it was always a dream
to attend that meeting in Zurich.

00:19:50.628 --> 00:19:54.748
I used to watch it on TV, athletics and
Zurich... That was just magical for me.

00:19:54.856 --> 00:19:57.176
Athletics is honestly one of
my favorite sports to watch.

00:19:57.331 --> 00:20:01.531
And then when someone
from Croatia makes it to the top,

00:20:01.709 --> 00:20:06.057
someone you can cheer for like a
neighbor, that's something special.

00:20:06.253 --> 00:20:09.291
Parents simply have to be involved...

00:20:09.421 --> 00:20:11.893
That's just how it is
with individual sports.

00:20:12.216 --> 00:20:16.920
Often those methods, as mentioned
earlier, are on the edge of what's okay.

00:20:17.080 --> 00:20:20.358
And you hear people say,
assuming the stories are even true,

00:20:20.535 --> 00:20:23.370
since they tend to get exaggerated,
'How can you do that to your own child?'

00:20:23.506 --> 00:20:25.835
But in truth, that's the only
person you can do that to.

00:20:25.976 --> 00:20:27.639
Because when it comes from a parent,

00:20:27.759 --> 00:20:29.928
the love and the good intention
are unquestionable. -Exactly.

00:20:30.036 --> 00:20:32.420
Let me go back for a second,
this isn't related to the topic,

00:20:32.544 --> 00:20:34.420
but it caught my interest.

00:20:34.621 --> 00:20:39.585
You mentioned Nadal's uncle switching
him from right to left hand.

00:20:40.577 --> 00:20:43.600
Is being a lefthanded person
really that much of an advantage?

00:20:43.715 --> 00:20:46.460
And where does that advantage
actually come from?

00:20:47.460 --> 00:20:50.820
Well, first of all,
he's not a 'classic' lefthander.

00:20:51.020 --> 00:20:53.340
We left-handers tend to
think a little differently.

00:20:53.820 --> 00:20:57.980
But in terms of tennis, there aren't
many left-handers at the top level,

00:20:58.220 --> 00:21:00.100
and it's tough to play
against them. -Why?

00:21:00.340 --> 00:21:02.940
Because the ball moves differently,
the serve is different,

00:21:03.860 --> 00:21:07.140
the spins are different,
everything changes.

00:21:07.620 --> 00:21:12.020
Your whole game plan shifts
when you're playing against a lefty.

00:21:12.220 --> 00:21:15.300
I never liked playing against
left-handers. -You didn't? -No.

00:21:15.540 --> 00:21:19.620
No, because I know how they think,
so I'd overanalyze everything

00:21:19.788 --> 00:21:23.188
and end up driving myself crazy.

00:21:23.820 --> 00:21:27.260
Everything just feels off
when you're up against them...

00:21:27.740 --> 00:21:33.660
So yeah, it's definitely an advantage.
I think his uncle sensed that.

00:21:33.860 --> 00:21:40.060
And knowing the kind of phenomenon
Nadal is, he understood it.

00:21:41.380 --> 00:21:43.660
People always talk about
Nadal's forehand,

00:21:43.860 --> 00:21:48.140
but when you watch his backhand,
it's actually like a forehand

00:21:48.340 --> 00:21:54.900
with his right hand. That's why
his backhand is so powerful.

00:21:55.180 --> 00:21:59.060
I see. So for him, it's essentially
a forehand with his right hand.

00:21:59.260 --> 00:22:04.500
That's right. You use it
to support your backhand.

00:22:05.020 --> 00:22:08.140
Yes, he uses his left hand,
but his right hand is the key.

00:22:08.340 --> 00:22:13.700
For my backhand, my left hand
must finish the stroke.

00:22:13.900 --> 00:22:18.420
Actually, no, I meant that for
right-handers, their right hand matters.

00:22:18.620 --> 00:22:22.980
So, he relies on that right hand...

00:22:23.380 --> 00:22:28.220
When you watch him, some people
might not have noticed that

00:22:28.460 --> 00:22:31.700
in a few of his backhands, it's as if
he smashes the ball like with a hammer,

00:22:31.940 --> 00:22:35.100
the ball flies at around 800 km/h,
at that kind of speed...

00:22:35.780 --> 00:22:41.700
His movement, his technique,
it's all special.

00:22:42.460 --> 00:22:49.240
He never had a crazy good serve,
but because he's left-handed,

00:22:49.870 --> 00:22:51.963
his serve was still super effective.

00:22:53.740 --> 00:22:57.900
I wouldn't say he was one of the best
servers of all time, he was solid,

00:22:58.100 --> 00:23:02.900
but being a lefty made his serve tricky.
He'd pull you way out wide,

00:23:04.180 --> 00:23:07.300
and then you're defending with
a backhand or with a forehand.

00:23:07.500 --> 00:23:13.500
If he were right-handed, that serve
wouldn't have been half as effective.

00:23:14.380 --> 00:23:18.940
But being left-handed added
50% more to its impact.

00:23:19.140 --> 00:23:24.060
So basically, like you said, he got a
left hand without losing the right one.

00:23:25.380 --> 00:23:34.940
That's why I really respect him.
He's truly special.

00:23:35.340 --> 00:23:38.788
But again, only someone close,
like an uncle, could do that.

00:23:38.923 --> 00:23:41.795
If some guy named Pedro from Mallorca
had come to him and said,

00:23:41.878 --> 00:23:44.216
'Hey, I think you should switch hands,'

00:23:44.360 --> 00:23:51.224
Exactly. -That's why you need that
family support. It has to be there.

00:23:52.898 --> 00:23:56.677
What do you think, what advice
would you give to parents today?

00:23:56.790 --> 00:23:59.110
I see it with my own kids,
they want to try a bit of everything.

00:23:59.219 --> 00:24:02.880
We've said before that it's not a bad
idea for kids to try several sports

00:24:02.926 --> 00:24:05.126
to figure out what suits them best.

00:24:05.827 --> 00:24:11.232
But do you think we should let them
just do whatever they want,

00:24:11.958 --> 00:24:17.318
a bit of dance, a bit of tennis,
a bit of football, a bit of gymnastics,

00:24:17.380 --> 00:24:24.580
or should parents be a bit more involved
in guiding and supporting them?

00:24:24.820 --> 00:24:27.100
At a certain point,
you have to be involved.

00:24:27.340 --> 00:24:32.580
I look at kids today, they jump
between 800 different sports.

00:24:32.820 --> 00:24:34.980
The moment they realize
they're not good at something,

00:24:35.220 --> 00:24:38.020
they immediately move on to
the next thing, and parents allow it.

00:24:38.424 --> 00:24:40.584
And in the end, they get lost.

00:24:41.130 --> 00:24:46.324
A parent has to be the voice of reason,
the one who calms them down

00:24:46.585 --> 00:24:49.985
and insists that they stick with
a sport for at least a few months,

00:24:50.277 --> 00:24:54.017
not switching every three days.

00:24:54.635 --> 00:24:59.833
I see this all the time
with young tennis players.

00:25:01.778 --> 00:25:03.548
I'll give you an example...

00:25:03.984 --> 00:25:08.029
I remember every single coach I had
since I was eight years old.

00:25:08.144 --> 00:25:14.161
I know their names, their surnames,
and exactly what they taught me.

00:25:14.664 --> 00:25:18.384
But if you ask a kid today what their
coach's name is, they have no idea.

00:25:19.540 --> 00:25:21.860
Because they already know
that in a month,

00:25:22.140 --> 00:25:24.620
when the coach starts
pushing them a bit,

00:25:24.860 --> 00:25:30.100
their parents won't allow anyone to
'talk to their child that way,'

00:25:33.320 --> 00:25:35.029
and they'll switch coaches.

00:25:35.300 --> 00:25:37.980
Coaches are being replaced like
products on an assembly line.

00:25:39.140 --> 00:25:44.020
That didn't exist before. -Yeah. The
whole sense of respect has collapsed.

00:25:44.380 --> 00:25:49.100
Exactly. Parents have to be
the ones who bring that stability.

00:25:49.340 --> 00:25:53.020
Sure, you can give your child some
freedom, but at a certain point,

00:25:53.300 --> 00:25:56.900
you have to tell them
it's time to get serious,

00:25:57.140 --> 00:25:59.420
if they really want to pursue it.

00:25:59.660 --> 00:26:03.060
And if they don't, then let them
play sports recreationally.

00:26:03.338 --> 00:26:07.094
The driving from one place to the next
is all fine if you've got the time.

00:26:08.176 --> 00:26:11.680
But then parents wait around for them,
hover over everything...

00:26:11.861 --> 00:26:17.581
Sometimes, you also need to just let
the kids go and figure things out.

00:26:17.719 --> 00:26:22.055
The mistake parents make today is that
they give their kids too much,

00:26:22.206 --> 00:26:25.453
and then the kids get overwhelmed
and can't handle the pressure.

00:26:26.079 --> 00:26:27.519
Balance is key.

00:26:28.794 --> 00:26:33.234
A child has to be a child. You have to
let them grow up and make mistakes.

00:26:33.325 --> 00:26:36.758
You can't prevent them from making
mistakes. Let them fail sometimes,

00:26:36.880 --> 00:26:40.428
let them fall a bit, because
if you never let them fall,

00:26:40.560 --> 00:26:45.500
one day they'll fall hard,
and they won't be able to get back up.

00:26:45.781 --> 00:26:51.117
But if they fall a little, shake it off,
stand up, and keep going. -Exactly.

00:26:51.980 --> 00:26:56.100
Parents also need to work on themselves,
so they don't make big mistakes.

00:26:56.380 --> 00:27:00.780
Absolutely, I completely agree.
I say the same thing to my own kids.

00:27:01.020 --> 00:27:03.420
Especially parents
in those formative years,

00:27:03.700 --> 00:27:06.060
when puberty starts, when new
challenges and changes come,

00:27:06.300 --> 00:27:08.340
and that phase in sport
when things don't go well,

00:27:08.540 --> 00:27:11.180
and the child just wants to give up...
Anyone would.

00:27:11.420 --> 00:27:15.500
The parent's role is not to
push too hard, but to guide,

00:27:15.700 --> 00:27:19.620
to navigate, like we say.
To nudge them a little.

00:27:19.820 --> 00:27:22.700
I always tell my kids:
"Try it for six months.

00:27:22.940 --> 00:27:26.300
You don't have to switch through 60
sports. Stick with it for six months,

00:27:26.445 --> 00:27:28.765
and if you don't like it
after that, fine, change.

00:27:28.894 --> 00:27:31.543
But you can't just keep changing
and changing endlessly."

00:27:31.747 --> 00:27:34.231
Exactly. I totally agree with that.

00:27:34.430 --> 00:27:41.670
Agassi once said that tennis is
the loneliest sport in the world.

00:27:43.540 --> 00:27:48.370
And for me, the first thing
that comes to mind

00:27:48.554 --> 00:27:52.386
when I think of tennis is solitude.
You're alone.

00:27:52.590 --> 00:27:56.012
From those formative years,
12 years and up,

00:27:56.231 --> 00:27:59.271
when tournaments start,
and they start early.

00:27:59.660 --> 00:28:02.980
When we went to tournaments,
not all of us were outgoing

00:28:03.300 --> 00:28:08.509
or eager to make friends,
but we were a group, a little crew.

00:28:08.806 --> 00:28:10.743
We were strong together.

00:28:10.795 --> 00:28:13.977
Someone in the group would be bold
enough to go talk to the Dinamo kids.

00:28:14.100 --> 00:28:15.980
We'd be playing in places like Skradin.

00:28:16.220 --> 00:28:20.360
Not all of us were brave, but
someone was, and then we'd tag along,

00:28:20.610 --> 00:28:23.180
talk a bit, mix with others...

00:28:23.420 --> 00:28:27.291
In tennis, you do everything
on your own. There's no one.

00:28:29.028 --> 00:28:33.721
And then you're pulled out of
regular life, you leave school...

00:28:34.015 --> 00:28:40.335
So tell me, isn't that just
too much to ask of a child?

00:28:40.555 --> 00:28:43.847
Even today, when that's become
a kind of norm,

00:28:44.031 --> 00:28:47.324
isn't it still an enormous sacrifice
just to maybe reach something?

00:28:48.580 --> 00:28:51.540
Yes, it is a lot, but maybe
that's just the way the times are.

00:28:51.780 --> 00:28:57.340
They did pull me out of school, but
I wish we had online schooling then.

00:28:57.740 --> 00:29:03.220
If I'd had access to a laptop,
it would've made a huge difference.

00:29:03.500 --> 00:29:06.020
I had so much free time
and nothing to do with it.

00:29:06.500 --> 00:29:10.460
If online school had existed,
it would've been great.

00:29:10.980 --> 00:29:15.100
But then again, who ever asked us
if we had any wishes or needs?

00:29:15.380 --> 00:29:22.860
Who asked me, at 15 or 17 years old,
if I was feeling pressure? No one.

00:29:23.100 --> 00:29:29.300
No one said anything.
It was just: "Go, play, move forward."

00:29:29.940 --> 00:29:34.460
And now, it's all like: "Oh no, is it
too much for him? Will he burn out?"

00:29:34.860 --> 00:29:37.900
Everyone's so careful
about every little thing.

00:29:38.740 --> 00:29:41.740
But that's exactly why rankings exist.

00:29:42.020 --> 00:29:43.860
That's why we can tell who's
going to be a champion and who's not.

00:29:44.140 --> 00:29:47.420
It's just obvious who can handle
pressure, who can take the hits...

00:29:47.660 --> 00:29:50.420
You have to take the hits sometimes,
or else you'll go down.

00:29:50.620 --> 00:29:52.980
The ones who can take the hits,
they come out on top.

00:29:53.660 --> 00:29:56.580
If you're afraid of making mistakes...

00:29:56.780 --> 00:30:02.740
Well, you're going to make them anyway.
That's inevitable. -Absolutely.

00:30:02.980 --> 00:30:05.420
And you can't succeed if you're afraid.

00:30:05.660 --> 00:30:08.580
I can't be sitting around worrying:
"Oh no, what if this happens..."

00:30:08.860 --> 00:30:12.140
Okay, not everyone's the same,
and sure, times have changed.

00:30:12.420 --> 00:30:15.620
But a champion is a champion.

00:30:15.860 --> 00:30:18.980
A real champion is born once
in a hundred thousand years,

00:30:19.660 --> 00:30:24.860
like Novak in tennis,
or Luka in football...

00:30:26.100 --> 00:30:29.660
And do you think anyone
asked them if it was hard?

00:30:29.900 --> 00:30:32.580
Of course, it was hard.
Of course, it was tough.

00:30:33.060 --> 00:30:36.780
It's tough for everyone at some point.
That's just how it is.

00:30:37.860 --> 00:30:41.780
I'm aware that once you
reach a certain level,

00:30:42.020 --> 00:30:44.780
there's no way you can keep up if
you don't have the right nutrition,

00:30:45.020 --> 00:30:49.020
the right support system, all of it.
Once you hit that senior level

00:30:49.220 --> 00:30:52.060
and you're tearing it up,
I get it completely...

00:30:52.260 --> 00:30:55.340
I told you before, back when
times were a lot more normal,

00:30:55.540 --> 00:30:59.740
I didn't go on my school trips in eighth
grade or third year of high school

00:30:59.940 --> 00:31:02.460
because of a tournament.

00:31:02.860 --> 00:31:09.140
And now, looking back as a parent, I ask
myself: was it really such a big deal

00:31:09.940 --> 00:31:14.380
if I had missed five days
of training for a school trip?

00:31:14.620 --> 00:31:18.140
A school trip is something beautiful,
a memory for life.

00:31:18.301 --> 00:31:21.941
And beyond that, it enriches you,
it might even help your career

00:31:22.158 --> 00:31:24.518
because you come back
a different person.

00:31:24.814 --> 00:31:31.214
Nowadays... of course, if a 14-year-old
has a strength coach and a nutritionist,

00:31:31.860 --> 00:31:36.292
and they hear there's a school trip
coming up, they'll say,

00:31:36.452 --> 00:31:38.652
'Are you crazy?
You can't go on a trip!

00:31:38.852 --> 00:31:41.480
Eating hot dogs for seven days,
skipping training…'

00:31:41.660 --> 00:31:46.417
But what I'm saying is - can you
do both when you're still young?

00:31:46.640 --> 00:31:52.737
I think you can. And honestly,
I think you should, up to a point.

00:31:54.220 --> 00:31:57.740
It also depends on the sport you're in,
but I believe it's possible,

00:31:57.980 --> 00:32:04.060
and that it has to be done that way.
Some things last a lifetime.

00:32:04.460 --> 00:32:08.780
You won’t remember hitting
20 forehands in practice,

00:32:09.020 --> 00:32:13.140
but you'd remember going
on a trip, as you said.

00:32:13.420 --> 00:32:17.060
Those things last. -Yes.

00:32:19.820 --> 00:32:22.220
Life is balance.

00:32:23.300 --> 00:32:26.820
In general, you must deal
with these things,

00:32:27.780 --> 00:32:33.180
but I think everyone
should experience them.

00:32:33.500 --> 00:32:38.260
That stays with you forever.
If you miss three training days,

00:32:38.500 --> 00:32:40.620
you won’t be better or worse.

00:32:41.340 --> 00:32:46.660
On the other hand, what you
just mentioned, those 20 forehands,

00:32:46.860 --> 00:32:49.580
and the fact you said at lunch,

00:32:50.180 --> 00:32:56.100
how many reps it takes for
the brain to maybe accept it.

00:32:57.180 --> 00:33:03.020
Yes, between 10k and 50k reps
for the brain to process it.

00:33:05.180 --> 00:33:09.140
They do 5-6 and say,
"I can't do it."

00:33:09.900 --> 00:33:17.540
What do you mean? You watch him,
should I send him home now or in 5 min.

00:33:18.140 --> 00:33:23.020
"I can't do it."
End of discussion.

00:33:23.820 --> 00:33:31.420
Friend, if you can't do it,
train, put it in your head, then...

00:33:34.009 --> 00:33:37.470
That's dedication.
-It's not for you.

00:33:39.900 --> 00:33:45.260
Dedication, but it becomes
too early, inhumane.

00:33:45.740 --> 00:33:50.039
I started at seven when
I went to school,

00:33:50.328 --> 00:33:54.140
now kids at 7-8-9
are semi-pros.

00:33:55.220 --> 00:34:00.214
They train 3-4 hours a day.
I think that's too much.

00:34:03.100 --> 00:34:07.620
At 7 years old? -8, 9 years,
but you will hit a wall.

00:34:07.860 --> 00:34:09.860
They will catch up to you.

00:34:10.700 --> 00:34:16.660
Then what? Five, six, seven,
eight? You can't.

00:34:17.120 --> 00:34:22.877
Your body can't take it.
Neither mind nor brain.

00:34:23.416 --> 00:34:31.127
You fall back, while the other
one catches up. Then panic.

00:34:32.564 --> 00:34:35.401
Then you wonder how
he caught up. -How?

00:34:35.927 --> 00:34:38.687
Change the coach, he's bad.

00:34:38.971 --> 00:34:44.159
Change everything. City,
coach, club. Nothing works.

00:34:45.280 --> 00:34:47.769
Yeah, yeah. Oh, my mother.

00:34:48.268 --> 00:34:50.708
You mentioned a few times...

00:34:52.700 --> 00:34:58.860
You mentioned a few times
that tennis is a gladiator sport.

00:35:00.660 --> 00:35:05.940
And when I thought about it...
I’ve loved tennis forever.

00:35:10.100 --> 00:35:16.260
It’s truly incredible. Look at
number one... Everyone comments.

00:35:16.540 --> 00:35:19.900
Number one, you're alone.
As Sampras said,

00:35:20.060 --> 00:35:22.580
"I can't pass the ball.
I have to solve it."

00:35:22.780 --> 00:35:29.060
No Ladić to save a penalty, no Šuker
to score or Bokšić. How is that?

00:35:29.300 --> 00:35:31.580
No one, just you.

00:35:32.340 --> 00:35:36.460
You simply accept it.
You know it's just you.

00:35:37.460 --> 00:35:42.220
Then comes adrenaline. -Adrenaline.
You must be good with yourself.

00:35:42.620 --> 00:35:48.540
Be your own friend,
with the racket, the situation.

00:35:48.820 --> 00:35:52.980
But, as you said, adrenaline.

00:35:53.300 --> 00:35:55.220
I decide. -Yes.

00:35:55.460 --> 00:35:57.620
I decide where to hit.

00:35:57.860 --> 00:36:00.420
I decide how...

00:36:00.740 --> 00:36:03.180
You have everything in your hands.

00:36:03.420 --> 00:36:08.500
I see he's done.
Will I let him back in the match?

00:36:09.380 --> 00:36:12.460
Many times, simply...

00:36:12.940 --> 00:36:21.020
What I don’t like in tennis now
is too many tournaments.

00:36:21.620 --> 00:36:24.340
No sport is like tennis,

00:36:25.300 --> 00:36:29.260
where the year ends if you
reach the Davis Cup final.

00:36:29.540 --> 00:36:37.300
You have Torino, Masters in late November,
and by mid-December, you must go to Australia.

00:36:37.500 --> 00:36:41.260
How is that normal? -Yes.
-It's impossible.

00:36:41.460 --> 00:36:45.180
You need rest, prep for Australia.

00:36:45.660 --> 00:36:50.100
Some matches last year
ended at 4 AM.

00:36:50.740 --> 00:36:57.047
4 AM? No way you’ll be ready.

00:36:58.980 --> 00:37:04.620
You go to sleep, reach the hotel,
and it's 7-8 AM.

00:37:05.580 --> 00:37:11.140
What? You sleep till 5 PM
and must play tomorrow.

00:37:14.420 --> 00:37:19.740
They started changing things,
but still... -Solution?

00:37:20.660 --> 00:37:27.980
Matches can't be played after 12,
but they can still last... -Cosmetics.

00:37:28.700 --> 00:37:35.180
Too many tournaments,
too many demands, it's too much...

00:37:35.460 --> 00:37:38.980
Every week, 2-3 tournaments,
every week something...

00:37:39.260 --> 00:37:43.900
You said it ends in November,
but mid-December, you’re in Australia.

00:37:44.100 --> 00:37:48.420
Can you choose tournaments
and take a break? -You can.

00:37:48.660 --> 00:37:52.140
If you want to stay on top.
-But how do you choose?

00:37:52.780 --> 00:37:56.020
You won’t take a break
when you're doing well.

00:37:56.700 --> 00:38:00.940
You must plan some schedule.

00:38:01.660 --> 00:38:07.580
Now, the good thing is that courts
are much more alike.

00:38:07.980 --> 00:38:11.500
Clay, grass, concrete.
It’s all balanced out.

00:38:11.740 --> 00:38:17.820
So, adaptation is easier.
Only on grass, running is tricky.

00:38:19.020 --> 00:38:24.540
But statistically, which I think
is crazy, in recent years

00:38:24.780 --> 00:38:29.940
longer rallies happen at Wimbledon
than at Roland Garros.

00:38:32.420 --> 00:38:39.660
Longer rallies? -Yes. It just looks
fast on TV with all the sliding.

00:38:39.980 --> 00:38:45.820
But grass is extremely slow.
The fastest Slam is Australia.

00:38:46.060 --> 00:38:52.180
That's why it's the best.
It rewards aggressive tennis.

00:38:52.420 --> 00:38:55.460
It rewards you when you attack,
you win the point.

00:38:55.700 --> 00:38:58.340
On fast courts, they return everything.

00:38:58.580 --> 00:39:02.740
So, you’d have a better chance
to win Paris than London now?

00:39:05.580 --> 00:39:11.500
Well, I mean, it's faster. In my time,
grass was like playing on ice. -Yeah.

00:39:13.180 --> 00:39:19.340
But too much... Now we had Australia,
then the American tour, then clay.

00:39:19.620 --> 00:39:24.420
Then comes the grass season.
After two weeks, Wimbledon, three.

00:39:24.660 --> 00:39:29.340
After Roland Garros last year,
there was the Olympics.

00:39:30.260 --> 00:39:38.500
What to play, what to skip? Now,
for money, these 1000s last two weeks.

00:39:39.940 --> 00:39:47.860
Madness. You play Madrid for two weeks,
Rome for two, a week off,

00:39:48.620 --> 00:39:53.420
then Paris for two weeks.
That's six weeks.

00:39:57.180 --> 00:39:59.980
So, the grass has slowed down?

00:40:00.660 --> 00:40:05.100
First, you're alone, right?
There's no one there.

00:40:05.380 --> 00:40:10.540
Second, no coach.
Now they allow a bit,

00:40:10.780 --> 00:40:17.020
but you said 90% of what Djokovic,
especially on big courts,

00:40:17.340 --> 00:40:20.020
what Djokovic tells you,
you don't hear it.

00:40:20.300 --> 00:40:22.980
So, no coach.
You're all on your own.

00:40:23.220 --> 00:40:25.380
He can't tell you anything.

00:40:25.620 --> 00:40:30.020
How do you communicate?
With signals?

00:40:30.260 --> 00:40:34.580
Now it's allowed if the player
is on the side of the coach,

00:40:34.820 --> 00:40:40.580
he can come... -Ten seconds?
-Not sure, maybe 10-15.

00:40:40.820 --> 00:40:43.780
In those 10-15 seconds,
you can say something.

00:40:44.020 --> 00:40:47.420
Novak didn’t come to you.

00:40:47.700 --> 00:40:52.900
He liked to shout from 100 meters.
Well, I can’t hear you. I don’t know.

00:40:53.980 --> 00:40:55.660
So...

00:40:59.300 --> 00:41:06.860
I still say, you enter alone,
you play alone... That’s just how it is.

00:41:07.100 --> 00:41:12.460
I can tell you to move your feet,
toss the ball higher, lower, and so on.

00:41:12.740 --> 00:41:18.260
But the tactics are clear.
They've played everyone 100 times.

00:41:18.500 --> 00:41:22.340
It's all analyzed before the match.
Stats show where each serve goes.

00:41:23.860 --> 00:41:29.020
But what if you notice
the opponent changed tactics?

00:41:29.420 --> 00:41:34.500
Do you let him know?
-Now we have an iPad in the box.

00:41:34.820 --> 00:41:39.060
You see he changed his serve pattern,
serves more there, so you tell him:

00:41:39.300 --> 00:41:44.724
"Step closer. Cover this side,
move forward, go back."

00:41:45.623 --> 00:41:49.669
There are those things, but still...

00:41:55.380 --> 00:42:03.380
Some players like it, some don’t.
With some, you must time it perfectly.

00:42:03.940 --> 00:42:09.277
It has nothing to do with tennis.
It just needs to click for them...

00:42:10.438 --> 00:42:15.074
A coach must know these things.
You have to be quick.

00:42:15.222 --> 00:42:20.527
It helps when you speak the same language.
Saying it in English isn't the same.

00:42:20.897 --> 00:42:27.285
By the time I translate, I lose it.
Saying it directly is much easier.

00:42:29.020 --> 00:42:33.241
Those are the two things.
You're alone, no coach.

00:42:33.481 --> 00:42:36.772
Well, there's a coach,
but it’s like he isn’t there.

00:42:37.351 --> 00:42:41.920
You can't just "pull the handbrake."
You can’t slow down.

00:42:42.857 --> 00:42:47.030
As Agassi says:
"One of the best things in tennis

00:42:47.461 --> 00:42:54.124
is that time never runs out.
As long as we play, I have a chance."

00:42:54.380 --> 00:43:00.220
Or as Nadal says: "I play every
point like my life depends on it."

00:43:00.460 --> 00:43:04.420
It's not like football,
where you lead 2-0, 1-0,

00:43:04.620 --> 00:43:09.100
or even 3-0. You draw back,
wait for them to come at you.

00:43:09.340 --> 00:43:13.940
Even in other sports.
In boxing, you win five rounds,

00:43:14.180 --> 00:43:17.751
so you take it easy,
your coach is there.

00:43:17.867 --> 00:43:19.467
Here, you can't do anything.

00:43:20.300 --> 00:43:26.860
Yeah, here you can't calculate.
You can't say, "I'm up 2-0 in sets,

00:43:27.180 --> 00:43:32.020
I'll rest now, lose one..."
That’s not how tennis works.

00:43:32.300 --> 00:43:38.500
Mentally, you're up 2-0 in sets,
lose the third. Now he has the edge.

00:43:38.700 --> 00:43:43.060
Momentum. -He has momentum,
going into the fifth. You know,

00:43:43.300 --> 00:43:48.220
you can't just say,
"I’ll step back, defend, maybe he..."

00:43:48.500 --> 00:43:52.780
Maybe he what? He won’t.
In your head, it's easier, I'm up two sets,

00:43:53.980 --> 00:43:58.780
maybe I can make a mistake.
But I can’t make too many,

00:43:58.878 --> 00:44:05.438
because it shifts fast,
and suddenly it’s 2-2 in sets.

00:44:05.547 --> 00:44:07.067
Where are you now?

00:44:09.260 --> 00:44:14.340
OK, they added a tie-break
in the fifth set, which is good.

00:44:14.580 --> 00:44:21.540
No more at Wimbledon 70-68,
where you have two "dead" players.

00:44:21.820 --> 00:44:25.020
The loser is "dead,"
the winner is also "dead."

00:44:25.300 --> 00:44:28.660
His next match is already lost...
-No chance.

00:44:28.860 --> 00:44:32.420
They played for three days.

00:44:35.100 --> 00:44:40.500
Some record. What record?
Both players are "dead."

00:44:41.300 --> 00:44:53.577
Fourth, and just as tough...
You're alone. There's no one there.

00:44:54.060 --> 00:44:59.218
You can’t relax. You don’t play
for half an hour, sprinting to 10.

00:44:59.404 --> 00:45:07.101
Every other game, you sit alone,
and that’s a ton of time.

00:45:07.514 --> 00:45:14.155
When it's not going well,
it feels endless.

00:45:14.637 --> 00:45:22.694
As Federer says, he's very positive,
and that helps him in tough moments.

00:45:23.060 --> 00:45:26.369
But if you have a problem,
you know what that is?

00:45:26.499 --> 00:45:29.259
You're alone, thinking about everything.

00:45:29.438 --> 00:45:33.758
You must focus on the next point,
but your mind is stuck on the last one.

00:45:33.942 --> 00:45:37.697
How do you...
Who can handle that?

00:45:39.500 --> 00:45:42.300
Well, it's not easy,
but you just get used to it.

00:45:42.540 --> 00:45:44.260
Everyone has a ritual.

00:45:44.500 --> 00:45:50.363
I had a ritual-looking at the crowd,
finding someone. It calmed me.

00:45:50.587 --> 00:45:56.137
Some watch people,
some sing something.

00:45:56.520 --> 00:46:03.825
Everyone has their own way,
everyone calms down differently.

00:46:05.180 --> 00:46:10.205
It all changes really fast,
really, really fast.

00:46:10.450 --> 00:46:14.659
Especially when playing the best.
You can't allow even a little...

00:46:14.861 --> 00:46:18.501
They eat you up. Like a shark.

00:46:18.959 --> 00:46:22.901
Once they smell blood,
you're done. You can't.

00:46:24.213 --> 00:46:26.881
For example, Novak...

00:46:27.940 --> 00:46:31.460
Sinner is like that, Alcaraz isn’t.

00:46:31.700 --> 00:46:37.780
Alcaraz plays one set, you may
not win a single point,

00:46:38.700 --> 00:46:43.500
but then he gives you the next.
He's... -Unstable? -Well, a bit...

00:46:44.900 --> 00:46:49.980
I prefer watching him.
Sinner is more like Novak.

00:46:51.380 --> 00:46:56.060
When Sinner grabs you,
you might as well leave.

00:46:56.300 --> 00:46:59.940
You have no chance.
He doesn't let go.

00:47:00.420 --> 00:47:04.780
He's always the same,
just grinds you down.

00:47:06.180 --> 00:47:10.700
Alright, after all that,
your reward at season’s end

00:47:10.980 --> 00:47:15.500
is that next year it means nothing.
You must defend points,

00:47:15.700 --> 00:47:19.860
and start all over again.
-You panic again.

00:47:20.060 --> 00:47:24.700
Here I defend something,
there I have a gap.

00:47:24.940 --> 00:47:27.620
How do I plan my schedule?
Maybe I invest more here,

00:47:27.821 --> 00:47:31.923
defend those,
then come the points,

00:47:32.470 --> 00:47:38.340
so panic kicks in... -Who does that?
You as a coach or him as a player?

00:47:38.540 --> 00:47:40.700
Well, coach and player decide.

00:47:41.580 --> 00:47:46.420
They discuss it. With Novak,
it was easy... I mean, "easy."

00:47:46.620 --> 00:47:51.100
During COVID, it wasn't.
There he could play, there he couldn't.

00:47:51.340 --> 00:47:56.460
They allow him, we pack up, we go.
Then a minister says no.

00:47:56.980 --> 00:48:01.980
So, you go back. But usually,
a schedule is made.

00:48:02.940 --> 00:48:08.060
One that can always,
of course, be changed.

00:48:08.260 --> 00:48:11.820
Rarely does a schedule
get fully completed.

00:48:12.300 --> 00:48:15.060
That’s a rare thing.

00:48:15.340 --> 00:48:18.780
Something can always happen,
God forbid, an injury,

00:48:18.980 --> 00:48:23.660
or if you have weaker results,
you might want to add a tournament.

00:48:24.220 --> 00:48:27.700
But more or less,
the schedule is known.

00:48:27.900 --> 00:48:33.060
A schedule is made
six to eight months in advance,

00:48:34.340 --> 00:48:38.460
maybe even longer,
and then it's followed.

00:48:38.597 --> 00:48:41.589
When you mentioned Novak,
what was the hardest thing

00:48:41.729 --> 00:48:44.049
to work on with him,
and what was the easiest?

00:48:47.460 --> 00:48:51.860
I don’t know what could be
"the hardest."

00:48:52.820 --> 00:48:56.100
What did he not accept?
What didn’t he want?

00:48:58.300 --> 00:49:03.500
He’s quite serious,
he likes biomechanics

00:49:03.740 --> 00:49:09.224
and many similar things.
It's not that I don’t believe in that,

00:49:09.355 --> 00:49:13.606
but some things have
nothing to do with biomechanics.

00:49:13.812 --> 00:49:17.762
You can't think about biomechanics,
about your hips, your knees,

00:49:17.999 --> 00:49:21.319
when you throw the ball
for your serve

00:49:21.731 --> 00:49:24.950
and the sun hits your eyes
and you can't see anything.

00:49:25.145 --> 00:49:26.945
You can't see the ball.

00:49:27.160 --> 00:49:30.320
For one second, you can't see the ball
and you hit it blindly.

00:49:30.568 --> 00:49:34.632
You can't think about your hip
while serving

00:49:34.843 --> 00:49:39.726
when you're as blind as a bat.
There's also the wind.

00:49:40.436 --> 00:49:43.991
It's about survival. And pressure, yes.
-Your pulse is 200.

00:49:44.598 --> 00:49:49.478
He wants to be perfect at it.
He's a perfectionist.

00:49:49.865 --> 00:49:55.225
I am too, but you have to
find some balance.

00:49:56.380 --> 00:50:02.060
And the easiest thing for me was that,
I’ve never seen a tennis player

00:50:02.300 --> 00:50:05.380
who can not play tennis
for two months

00:50:05.580 --> 00:50:11.660
and then play as if
he never even stopped.

00:50:12.220 --> 00:50:16.420
He plays like he had been training five
hours a day for the past two months.

00:50:16.620 --> 00:50:20.380
Such timing, such a feel for the court,
for the ball, for the space,

00:50:20.580 --> 00:50:22.940
I’ve never seen
anything like it in my life.

00:50:23.140 --> 00:50:26.460
Nadal is not like that.
He has to train every day, otherwise...

00:50:27.100 --> 00:50:30.140
Is it the psyche, or...
the feel in the hand?

00:50:30.300 --> 00:50:32.980
It’s simply the way you play.

00:50:33.140 --> 00:50:35.980
Nadal is wearing
himself out too much.

00:50:36.220 --> 00:50:40.060
Every training session of his
looks like there is no tomorrow.

00:50:40.220 --> 00:50:43.900
Each of his shots is
as if there is no tomorrow.

00:50:44.700 --> 00:50:49.540
It’s similar with Federer,
but with him, it looks more beautiful.

00:50:50.100 --> 00:50:55.940
But with him, it’s such timing,
such beauty.

00:50:56.260 --> 00:51:00.460
You watch and feel
almost hypnotized.

00:51:01.700 --> 00:51:05.540
And all of his preparation...
How he prepares, how he eats.

00:51:05.740 --> 00:51:11.060
Nutrition, training, it’s all one
experience, and it's beautiful to see.

00:51:11.300 --> 00:51:15.660
It’s beautiful to be part of that.
Yes, there are things

00:51:15.940 --> 00:51:22.405
you can’t even hold against him
when he’s won everything.

00:51:22.749 --> 00:51:33.931
Of course. -But, there’s some kind
of balance and public respect.

00:51:35.700 --> 00:51:42.020
It was phenomenal with him.
Those are things you can never forget.

00:51:44.860 --> 00:51:48.020
And if I never do anything
related to tennis,

00:51:48.220 --> 00:51:53.028
I’ll know that I was part of the team
of the greatest player in history.

00:51:53.263 --> 00:51:57.544
And with all those records,
even if I just sat there

00:51:57.917 --> 00:52:04.157
and carried rackets, it can still be
said that I did something.

00:52:08.220 --> 00:52:11.264
You once said that...
Is there something missing in tennis

00:52:11.378 --> 00:52:13.778
when it comes to that
sense of belonging,

00:52:13.892 --> 00:52:16.092
in the sense that you
don’t have your own club,

00:52:16.199 --> 00:52:18.799
you don’t have a league,
your own locker room,

00:52:18.968 --> 00:52:24.717
you don’t have a jersey, home fans...
I noticed you said about Đoković

00:52:27.380 --> 00:52:33.500
that he’s 5000 times more motivated
when he plays for Serbia, than otherwise.

00:52:33.653 --> 00:52:37.573
Let’s remember you when you played
for Croatia in the Davis Cup,

00:52:37.796 --> 00:52:40.396
not to mention Barcelona,

00:52:40.549 --> 00:52:45.589
where in singles, you won the last
four matches in five sets.

00:52:45.743 --> 00:52:49.343
So, that’s a huge patriotism
and a huge desire

00:52:49.511 --> 00:52:52.591
to do something for your country.

00:52:53.020 --> 00:52:56.660
Yes, with him, that’s very pronounced
and it’s something incredible.

00:52:56.940 --> 00:53:00.860
We saw that last year, when his goal
was to win the Olympic Games.

00:53:01.060 --> 00:53:04.740
And there was no way
he was going to lose that match.

00:53:04.940 --> 00:53:07.460
If they had played for 15 days in a row,
him and Alcaraz,

00:53:07.660 --> 00:53:11.900
he would have won that match.
It’s simply his desire.

00:53:12.100 --> 00:53:16.940
And when he plays for the Davis Cup
or any other Cup for Serbia,

00:53:17.140 --> 00:53:20.020
he gives his all.

00:53:20.660 --> 00:53:24.540
But we’re talking about you,
and you also gave your all

00:53:24.740 --> 00:53:29.260
in the last four matches,
all five sets. That’s 20 sets.

00:53:29.460 --> 00:53:31.500
That was something special.

00:53:31.700 --> 00:53:34.900
That was the first time I played
for Croatia in the Olympics.

00:53:34.982 --> 00:53:36.982
I was carrying the flag.

00:53:37.460 --> 00:53:45.327
One or two matches, I was the reason
why the match lasted five sets,

00:53:46.801 --> 00:53:51.309
but fatigue wasn’t an option.
I’m dead, but I’m not.

00:53:52.509 --> 00:53:59.127
It’s +400°C, but I’m playing.
I simply had to win that medal.

00:53:59.540 --> 00:54:04.300
I’m sorry, we also played doubles
and lost in five sets in the semifinals,

00:54:04.500 --> 00:54:07.740
but we could have won
at least a silver.

00:54:08.140 --> 00:54:11.660
But, at least we have that Davis Cup.

00:54:11.900 --> 00:54:15.100
What bothers me is,
that because of money,

00:54:15.300 --> 00:54:20.980
because of some interests,
and it doesn’t exist in sports,

00:54:21.180 --> 00:54:24.938
except in tennis,
where a football player comes,

00:54:25.823 --> 00:54:30.078
whom I highly respect
and who has won everything,

00:54:30.301 --> 00:54:36.602
and changes the rule in the oldest
tennis competition ever.

00:54:36.929 --> 00:54:38.729
And that’s because of money.

00:54:38.936 --> 00:54:42.944
He brought his company
that entered tennis

00:54:43.093 --> 00:54:48.725
to turn the Davis Cup
into a World Championship

00:54:49.494 --> 00:54:53.294
where everyone will play
in one place.

00:54:53.620 --> 00:54:57.003
It’s good for the host country.
When Malaga was the host

00:54:57.168 --> 00:54:59.968
and when the Spaniards were playing,
the stadiums were full.

00:55:00.128 --> 00:55:06.019
But when Canada and Chile played,
only five people showed up.

00:55:08.700 --> 00:55:12.300
Tennis is not football.
It doesn’t work like that.

00:55:12.580 --> 00:55:15.740
When home matches are played,
people come to watch, to cheer.

00:55:16.020 --> 00:55:21.220
We just played in Osijek against
Slovakia and the atmosphere was great.

00:55:21.420 --> 00:55:25.140
It was crazy, the atmosphere.
And that’s what’s missing, that energy.

00:55:25.340 --> 00:55:27.620
And when it was in South America,
when it was in Argentina,

00:55:27.820 --> 00:55:30.260
it wasn’t pleasant to play there,
but it was a blast.

00:55:30.460 --> 00:55:33.220
When we played against Argentina,
Maradona came,

00:55:33.460 --> 00:55:35.620
and the match was interrupted
for 15 minutes.

00:55:35.820 --> 00:55:37.820
The match was interrupted!

00:55:38.060 --> 00:55:41.300
He came into our locker room,
I even have a picture at home.

00:55:41.540 --> 00:55:44.700
So, it was a break in the game.
Tennis was interrupted.

00:55:44.940 --> 00:55:47.540
The Argentinians were singing,
we were singing.

00:55:47.780 --> 00:55:51.540
We didn’t know what we were singing,
but we were singing. Maradona came.

00:55:52.540 --> 00:55:54.980
We could’ve sung
for another two hours.

00:55:55.180 --> 00:55:59.580
Tennis didn’t matter anymore.
And that’s incredible.

00:55:59.860 --> 00:56:04.100
The stadium was full,
maybe 7-8 thousand people.

00:56:04.420 --> 00:56:06.740
But, for me, it was a blast
playing there.

00:56:06.940 --> 00:56:10.260
So, 8 000 people are singing,
cheering, and provoking you,

00:56:10.460 --> 00:56:13.780
but for me, that’s a blast.
-You’d play there every day.

00:56:13.980 --> 00:56:17.900
Yes, every day, because in the end,
when Ljubo and I won

00:56:18.100 --> 00:56:21.400
the doubles match, 8 000 people
stood up and applauded,

00:56:21.514 --> 00:56:24.033
they were singing to me.
-Impossible.

00:56:25.054 --> 00:56:29.189
And even if they hadn’t,
it doesn’t matter,

00:56:29.323 --> 00:56:32.407
but the atmosphere was incredible.
They even helped me.

00:56:35.100 --> 00:56:38.460
Then it all collapsed
and went bankrupt,

00:56:39.060 --> 00:56:43.540
and now that Davis Cup
is neither here nor there.

00:56:44.860 --> 00:56:48.860
It would be like
if Nadal and Federer

00:56:49.540 --> 00:56:52.540
came and changed the rules
of the Champions League.

00:56:52.900 --> 00:56:54.380
What would they say to them:

00:56:54.660 --> 00:57:00.154
'You two, respect,
but those are the doors, so leave.'

00:57:00.942 --> 00:57:06.654
And this in tennis, not padel.
Tennis is a global sport.

00:57:09.871 --> 00:57:14.130
Yes, I don’t understand that part.

00:57:14.936 --> 00:57:18.925
There’s money, madness,
but where are we now? Nowhere.

00:57:20.060 --> 00:57:21.100
Yes.

00:57:22.740 --> 00:57:26.460
When you said about Đoković,
that he can take a break...

00:57:26.700 --> 00:57:30.940
What does a week
at a tournament look like?

00:57:32.540 --> 00:57:35.980
How much do you train,
how much do you play?

00:57:36.620 --> 00:57:40.700
You can’t, when you go to
a tournament, overdo it with training.

00:57:41.820 --> 00:57:44.576
Preparation is done before you
go to the tournament.

00:57:44.755 --> 00:57:46.597
When you arrive at the tournament,
training depends

00:57:46.678 --> 00:57:48.324
on the type of competition.

00:57:48.425 --> 00:57:51.050
If you’re playing a Grand Slam,
you play every other day,

00:57:51.161 --> 00:57:54.074
and if you’ve played 3-4 sets,
the next day you have

00:57:54.236 --> 00:57:56.792
a training session
of 45 minutes maximum.

00:57:57.300 --> 00:58:02.988
You work on something
that maybe wasn’t good.

00:58:03.258 --> 00:58:05.698
The very next day?
-Yes, right away.

00:58:06.140 --> 00:58:08.180
Even though you play again
the day after tomorrow?

00:58:08.460 --> 00:58:16.691
No matter. -That’s fascinating.
Some say you lose the feel,

00:58:17.253 --> 00:58:21.902
some say it’s the mind,
but why do you play today,

00:58:22.433 --> 00:58:25.673
sometimes even tomorrow,
and regardless of what

00:58:25.849 --> 00:58:29.980
you play tomorrow afternoon,
you still have to train in the morning.

00:58:30.160 --> 00:58:33.176
Is that pure activation or...?

00:58:34.504 --> 00:58:39.730
It depends. Some people need to
warm up for 45 minutes before a match.

00:58:39.942 --> 00:58:43.742
And that’s 45 minutes
of intense warm-up.

00:58:44.100 --> 00:58:47.820
That’s not what we see
on the court, but inside?

00:58:47.980 --> 00:58:53.180
Exactly, it’s intense.
Some people 15 minutes, some 20.

00:58:53.279 --> 00:58:55.559
It all depends on the person.

00:58:57.180 --> 00:59:00.060
Novak did another great thing.

00:59:00.340 --> 00:59:05.020
He won a Grand Slam,
without the day off in between.

00:59:05.143 --> 00:59:07.593
And that’s because of
some other factors.

00:59:08.460 --> 00:59:13.140
It can be played like that.
So, it’s all in the mind. -Yes.

00:59:14.060 --> 00:59:16.780
But that’s some kind of ritual.
They go to the gym a bit,

00:59:17.060 --> 00:59:21.220
then some ice baths,
a bit of this, a bit of that…

00:59:22.780 --> 00:59:27.700
But if the match was long,
or if a rest day is taken,

00:59:28.540 --> 00:59:33.220
then you warm up longer on match day,
or if the match was easier,

00:59:33.700 --> 00:59:40.980
you train, not longer than 45 minutes.
It’s enough to just get a good workout.

00:59:41.220 --> 00:59:45.820
How exhausting is it to play,
both mentally and physically,

00:59:46.060 --> 00:59:51.540
a match of 3-4, even 5 hours?
Are you dead after that?

00:59:51.820 --> 00:59:55.754
Then you have many
ups and downs.

00:59:55.857 --> 00:59:58.017
It also depends on
where you’re playing.

00:59:58.188 --> 01:00:00.388
For example, if you’re
playing in Australia

01:00:00.558 --> 01:00:03.730
in those extreme heat conditions,
or a night match,

01:00:03.940 --> 01:00:06.060
there’s a huge difference.

01:00:06.198 --> 01:00:09.347
Then you have the US Open,
where there’s a lot of humidity.

01:00:09.473 --> 01:00:14.035
You can wring out your sock
after a few games.

01:00:14.856 --> 01:00:17.056
Those are the ups and downs.

01:00:17.217 --> 01:00:21.097
The question is only
how you’ll handle it.

01:00:21.315 --> 01:00:26.395
You can’t train for that.
That’s the good and bad part.

01:00:26.763 --> 01:00:29.923
It's good, because you
don’t know what to expect.

01:00:30.132 --> 01:00:35.394
You can’t play like
it’s a friendly match.

01:00:35.489 --> 01:00:38.691
Who cares about a friendly match,
and who cares about a friendly game.

01:00:38.786 --> 01:00:41.306
And you don’t know what to expect.

01:00:43.580 --> 01:00:50.300
You can be in the best shape,
and still be hit by panic or cramps.

01:00:50.465 --> 01:00:53.899
You don’t know how that could happen,
you’re in the best shape,

01:00:54.043 --> 01:00:56.682
you did the best preparations.
What do you do now?

01:00:56.841 --> 01:00:59.120
You don’t have
a physiotherapist for cramps,

01:00:59.278 --> 01:01:01.400
you have to take care of it yourself.

01:01:01.542 --> 01:01:03.736
Sometimes it passes,
sometimes it doesn’t.

01:01:04.014 --> 01:01:10.135
These are huge shocks
for the body. As for this...

01:01:10.231 --> 01:01:12.762
So how do you train the next day?

01:01:13.060 --> 01:01:17.340
I’ll give you an example
of how it is with us.

01:01:17.940 --> 01:01:20.100
Sometimes, when I talk to someone,
this isn’t the first time,

01:01:20.380 --> 01:01:23.420
I’m sometimes ashamed
of how much we train. Really.

01:01:25.060 --> 01:01:28.524
Let’s take the Premier League
as an example where I worked.

01:01:28.712 --> 01:01:32.649
Once a year, and only there,
nowhere else,

01:01:33.040 --> 01:01:35.720
when Christmas is approaching,
when Boxing Day is

01:01:35.882 --> 01:01:38.867
on December 26th, they play
on December 28th,

01:01:39.014 --> 01:01:43.031
and there’s less than 48 hours
between two matches.

01:01:43.234 --> 01:01:49.219
That’s when the alert goes off.
It’s been like that for years.

01:01:49.369 --> 01:01:52.602
When that period comes,
then the strategy is made

01:01:52.774 --> 01:01:57.555
with the medical team to decide
who can play and who cannot.

01:01:57.928 --> 01:02:01.883
And you have 25 players,
you can rotate them,

01:02:02.027 --> 01:02:03.867
do whatever you want...

01:02:04.000 --> 01:02:06.289
And that only happens
that one single time.

01:02:06.424 --> 01:02:08.960
You, in fact, play like
that all the time. -Yes.

01:02:09.112 --> 01:02:12.112
When you play a normal tournament
that lasts a week,

01:02:12.439 --> 01:02:15.859
you can have one day off
and then play every day.

01:02:16.321 --> 01:02:21.121
A Grand Slam, every other day,
but then it rains.

01:02:22.142 --> 01:02:26.563
And then again, there’s injustice,
because, for example,

01:02:26.641 --> 01:02:28.695
Wimbledon has two roofs.

01:02:29.076 --> 01:02:31.356
Those who play under the roof
finish their match,

01:02:31.567 --> 01:02:34.887
and since it can rain
for 2-3 days at Wimbledon,

01:02:35.018 --> 01:02:38.476
the others fall behind
and have to play every day.

01:02:38.593 --> 01:02:41.033
Do they need to catch up?
-That’s right.

01:02:42.820 --> 01:02:48.660
So, if you’re better,
you still have privileges.

01:02:53.300 --> 01:02:58.220
But if you play for 4-5 hours today,
there’s no need to train tomorrow.

01:02:58.900 --> 01:03:03.330
You can stretch, you can run
a little in the park, and that’s it.

01:03:03.479 --> 01:03:05.319
And get a good night’s sleep.

01:03:05.559 --> 01:03:09.799
Because, when you go
to the courts, warm up,

01:03:10.140 --> 01:03:13.860
come back, you lose 5-6 hours.
For what?

01:03:15.540 --> 01:03:20.140
So, when those tough matches
were played,

01:03:20.340 --> 01:03:24.537
there was no training the next day.
You simply skip it.

01:03:24.700 --> 01:03:27.900
You stretch a little and we
see each other on match day,

01:03:28.180 --> 01:03:36.300
with a longer warm-up, and that’s it.
-Looking at this now, you cover

01:03:36.540 --> 01:03:41.194
a long period, like I do in football.
There’s the period when you played,

01:03:41.295 --> 01:03:43.712
and now when you’re a coach.

01:03:43.883 --> 01:03:48.413
Has tennis changed, and if it has,
how much has it changed?

01:03:48.594 --> 01:03:52.114
I’m not talking about faster balls,
better rackets, or surfaces

01:03:52.321 --> 01:03:54.961
which you said have become
more equal.

01:03:55.606 --> 01:03:58.585
I’m talking about technical
and tactical changes.

01:03:58.720 --> 01:04:01.952
Or is there no room for changes
in individual sports?

01:04:02.859 --> 01:04:08.884
﻿I tell everyone there is
a forehand, a backhand and serve.

01:04:09.127 --> 01:04:17.498
If you don't do it, the other will.
Technically, they don't play better.

01:04:19.040 --> 01:04:25.334
Few of them come to the net,
few of them use the volley. -Why?

01:04:25.577 --> 01:04:32.457
Simply because the surfaces are slower
and they're afraid of getting passed.

01:04:32.903 --> 01:04:37.078
They don’t feel comfortable,
they're not used to it.

01:04:38.374 --> 01:04:43.843
Matches last longer,
everyone serves over 220.

01:04:44.620 --> 01:04:48.260
Is the surface slower?
-Yes, it's slower.

01:04:48.500 --> 01:04:51.220
Returns are better than before.

01:04:52.020 --> 01:04:55.540
The thing that will be equalized
is there will be no difference

01:04:55.780 --> 01:05:00.686
between the first and second serve.
In a few years, it will be like that.

01:05:00.851 --> 01:05:03.115
Wasn't it the same with you?
-Well, no.

01:05:03.327 --> 01:05:11.687
We have a French player whose
average second serve is 220.

01:05:12.220 --> 01:05:18.307
Average? -That means,
first serve 230, second 237.

01:05:19.860 --> 01:05:23.820
Simply, more and more
these bomb serves will be used,

01:05:24.420 --> 01:05:27.060
because they have more faith in it.

01:05:27.620 --> 01:05:32.620
Even though you're risking?
-Well, you have two serves.

01:05:32.794 --> 01:05:35.740
If you can't hit one of the two, then...

01:05:37.621 --> 01:05:41.395
If you hit it weaker, he'll attack you.

01:05:43.380 --> 01:05:48.980
More or less, it's played tactically.

01:05:49.220 --> 01:05:59.380
They all know how each one plays.
At any given moment, it's clear.

01:05:59.700 --> 01:06:02.580
I know 90% of them.

01:06:02.780 --> 01:06:05.940
The player you're facing
can't surprise you.

01:06:06.102 --> 01:06:08.702
Could he invent something new?
-Well, no...

01:06:08.831 --> 01:06:14.895
He can surprise me once in 50,
when out of desperation he hits.

01:06:16.660 --> 01:06:21.413
But rarely does anyone surprise me
that I'd say: "Look at this!"

01:06:22.543 --> 01:06:28.503
He can surprise me with a set,
but the whole match, hardly.

01:06:29.980 --> 01:06:35.346
Simply, they train like that,

01:06:35.540 --> 01:06:40.354
but that training can't be
transferred to the match,

01:06:41.575 --> 01:06:46.575
because you never know what awaits
you and when it awaits you.

01:06:47.780 --> 01:06:51.420
Who comes to court. -There's
also the opponent, of course.

01:06:51.900 --> 01:06:56.580
That's the key. Bravo!
A few more questions.

01:06:56.952 --> 01:07:02.395
Is there friendship in tennis,
in the white circus, as they say?

01:07:02.689 --> 01:07:07.169
And enmity? Who are you
on good terms with?

01:07:07.394 --> 01:07:13.942
You said you didn't exchange
even 16 words with Sampras?

01:07:14.447 --> 01:07:18.007
No, he's a weirdo.
I was on good terms with Agassi.

01:07:18.160 --> 01:07:20.317
And with Courier, too.

01:07:20.575 --> 01:07:26.067
One of my best friends was the current
ATP president, Andrea Gaudenzi.

01:07:27.126 --> 01:07:33.726
In my time it was more friendship,
players were closer,

01:07:34.100 --> 01:07:36.620
and they didn't travel with teams.

01:07:36.860 --> 01:07:39.700
Now every player has at least
two people on his team.

01:07:39.900 --> 01:07:42.660
The better ones can have three
or more people on their team.

01:07:42.860 --> 01:07:46.340
So, they're with their own crew.

01:07:46.494 --> 01:07:49.932
I'm on good terms with everyone.

01:07:50.262 --> 01:07:53.284
Now it's more about respect.

01:07:53.778 --> 01:07:56.858
They're not crazy friends.

01:07:57.190 --> 01:08:01.070
They won't go to dinner
or hang out much.

01:08:01.435 --> 01:08:03.839
Everyone respects everyone.

01:08:04.039 --> 01:08:09.599
They hang out in their team
with everyone. -And the coaches?

01:08:09.882 --> 01:08:15.882
Fitness and physical coaches...
-It's like the engine is running.

01:08:16.123 --> 01:08:20.732
From tournament to tournament.
Pack up and let's go.

01:08:21.420 --> 01:08:24.260
So, before, people hung out
more than now?

01:08:24.580 --> 01:08:29.060
It must be, if you don't want
me to go to dinner alone.

01:08:29.300 --> 01:08:34.020
If you didn't take Kuzzi?
Then knock on Agassi's door.

01:08:34.111 --> 01:08:36.151
Because it's the same for him. -Yes.

01:08:40.780 --> 01:08:48.900
Agassi once said: "In tennis every
match is a miniature of life."

01:08:49.420 --> 01:08:53.900
Even the terms in tennis
are connected to life.

01:08:54.140 --> 01:09:04.787
Serve, favor, break, advantage...
Even love.

01:09:10.900 --> 01:09:15.060
Would you do it all over again?
Would you play tennis again?

01:09:15.278 --> 01:09:17.197
Is this your life? -Yes!

01:09:17.940 --> 01:09:24.300
I would choose tennis again, but maybe
I would do something differently.

01:09:24.540 --> 01:09:30.900
I don't know if it would be
better or worse? But it's tennis.

01:09:31.780 --> 01:09:34.460
Does your son play tennis?
-Yes, he does.

01:09:34.660 --> 01:09:38.420
But I think you're destined
to play one sport.

01:09:38.519 --> 01:09:41.275
The one above wanted it.

01:09:42.064 --> 01:09:47.329
And that's simply love.
You have to love what you do.

01:09:48.700 --> 01:09:53.380
I love all sports, but still,
tennis is tennis.

01:09:54.940 --> 01:09:59.700
I'm glad I decided
about my own destiny. -Yes.

01:10:00.044 --> 01:10:03.004
No one else can decide that.

01:10:03.220 --> 01:10:06.100
Am I cheating?
Have I crossed the line?

01:10:06.300 --> 01:10:11.500
Am I offside by a millimeter or two?
There’s no such thing.

01:10:11.780 --> 01:10:14.980
I can’t blame anyone.

01:10:16.780 --> 01:10:20.860
Because I’m always
the only one responsible.

01:10:21.100 --> 01:10:26.276
I made the decisions.
Good, bad, wrong, right.

01:10:26.534 --> 01:10:31.100
But I made them myself.
-I completely agree with that.

01:10:31.700 --> 01:10:35.780
If there are athletes,
you belong among them.

01:10:36.020 --> 01:10:42.114
Perišić and you, if you had
trained volleyball or handball,

01:10:42.442 --> 01:10:48.820
you’d still be national team players.
Or football, same thing.

01:10:49.060 --> 01:10:53.700
There are many specifics.
These other sports.

01:10:53.855 --> 01:10:55.935
But an athlete is an athlete.

01:10:56.160 --> 01:11:04.090
That’s right, an athlete
will be good at any sport, but still...

01:11:04.759 --> 01:11:07.199
The best is in football.

01:11:10.460 --> 01:11:14.380
I saw a football player
playing top-level tennis.

01:11:14.733 --> 01:11:18.029
Diego Forlán plays
Challenger tournaments.

01:11:18.113 --> 01:11:20.420
You have to reach that level.

01:11:22.252 --> 01:11:25.006
You have to step onto the court,

01:11:25.226 --> 01:11:29.092
because these are people
who play serious tennis.

01:11:29.641 --> 01:11:35.001
He played,didn’t win,
played doubles, but he plays.

01:11:36.212 --> 01:11:43.692
And that’s Challenger, and at
the World Championship level...

01:11:44.804 --> 01:11:47.816
There are also many tennis players
who play top-level golf,

01:11:47.948 --> 01:11:50.153
but they’re not Tiger Woods.

01:11:50.417 --> 01:11:55.559
They go to tournaments,
play among themselves, incredible.

01:11:55.760 --> 01:11:59.637
Maybe they didn’t get the score,
not even close,

01:11:59.762 --> 01:12:02.122
the crowd and all that...

01:12:02.432 --> 01:12:06.072
It’s like in football,
when they play well...

01:12:06.900 --> 01:12:12.981
But if you put him in a match,
and someone slides in from 30 meters

01:12:13.231 --> 01:12:16.580
with their boots, it’s over...
-That’s right.

01:12:20.209 --> 01:12:23.289
You shouldn’t have brought him in now,
but when he was seven...

01:12:23.490 --> 01:12:26.184
Then it’s a different question.
-That’s right.

01:12:26.536 --> 01:12:30.036
We can’t know, but something...

01:12:30.297 --> 01:12:32.617
Something led you there.

01:12:33.300 --> 01:12:38.302
Maybe you were in two sports,
but you chose this one.

01:12:39.340 --> 01:12:45.380
Something happened, that’s why
someone chose the sport they’re good at.

01:12:45.620 --> 01:12:49.340
It’s simple,
there are no rules here.

01:12:50.020 --> 01:12:55.140
In the end, for our Drago Marić,
for the kids, for the parents...

01:12:55.940 --> 01:12:58.580
So, your son Emanuel plays tennis?

01:12:59.420 --> 01:13:03.820
Do you advise him in the same way
Srđan advised you, or not?

01:13:04.340 --> 01:13:10.500
I try, but how much he listens
to me, that’s a different question.

01:13:12.700 --> 01:13:18.820
But I feel there’s some
kind of resistance.

01:13:19.780 --> 01:13:22.540
I’d like him to ask me more...

01:13:22.820 --> 01:13:25.620
But I leave him...

01:13:25.900 --> 01:13:30.020
He has his coaches, his path,
I’m here when he needs something.

01:13:31.460 --> 01:13:33.220
I help him.

01:13:34.860 --> 01:13:38.140
He’s currently
the best Croatian junior.

01:13:38.540 --> 01:13:42.740
Honestly, there’s
no magic crystal ball

01:13:43.180 --> 01:13:48.180
to tell us what will happen
to him in life or in tennis.

01:13:49.180 --> 01:13:52.100
I’m always here for everything.

01:13:52.540 --> 01:13:55.972
Parents should be present
in their child’s life.

01:13:56.235 --> 01:14:01.511
They shouldn’t force, but they should
be there to help, with advice,

01:14:01.658 --> 01:14:06.610
in one way or another, however they can,
but they have to be present.

01:14:07.073 --> 01:14:13.753
Parents are an important link
in that chain, but again...

01:14:14.300 --> 01:14:18.220
Parents can’t transfer their
ambitions onto their children,

01:14:18.460 --> 01:14:23.980
because then it becomes a vicious
circle that ends in failure.

01:14:24.220 --> 01:14:30.500
And in the end, both the child
and the parent are left frustrated.

01:14:30.780 --> 01:14:34.300
And that turns into a disaster.

01:14:34.700 --> 01:14:37.977
So I want to be his father,
to have a father-son relationship.

01:14:38.118 --> 01:14:42.501
If he needs advice, I’m here,
but I don’t want to be his coach.

01:14:43.020 --> 01:14:50.350
Never, because I’ve seen many
cases where it didn’t end well.

01:14:51.424 --> 01:14:56.347
Especially in tennis, better not.

01:14:56.831 --> 01:15:03.408
You said that professional sport
isn’t healthy.

01:15:04.980 --> 01:15:08.500
Although, on the other hand,
sport is the best and purest thing,

01:15:08.678 --> 01:15:10.558
if you find that balance.

01:15:10.845 --> 01:15:15.960
But would you recommend
individual or team sports?

01:15:16.320 --> 01:15:18.968
Or should it depend on where
someone finds themselves?

01:15:19.263 --> 01:15:28.303
Maybe where someone finds themselves.
I’ve always been for individual sports.

01:15:28.530 --> 01:15:31.210
Although football is my favorite sport.

01:15:34.106 --> 01:15:40.334
But you can’t force someone
to play or do something.

01:15:40.543 --> 01:15:43.771
I think a child,
whether male or female,

01:15:43.913 --> 01:15:47.538
has to decide for themselves
which sport to choose.

01:15:47.711 --> 01:15:50.991
Which sport they’ll choose,
I can’t say.

01:15:51.168 --> 01:15:54.801
I can’t say this is easier,
or that is harder,

01:15:54.965 --> 01:16:00.354
everything is difficult.
It’s hard to be a top athlete.

01:16:00.692 --> 01:16:04.065
If someone thinks it’s easy...

01:16:04.674 --> 01:16:10.276
Now they look at Instagram,
and they see the end result...

01:16:11.582 --> 01:16:14.805
But how much blood, sweat,
how many ups and downs there were...

01:16:15.010 --> 01:16:18.360
It doesn’t matter if you have a team
with you or if you’re alone.

01:16:18.518 --> 01:16:23.209
Maybe it’s harder when you’re alone,
you’re happy and afraid by yourself.

01:16:23.442 --> 01:16:28.144
In football, there are 11 people,
you’re happy together,

01:16:28.260 --> 01:16:35.140
you cry together. But it’s hard.
Whoever wants to be an athlete

01:16:35.660 --> 01:16:40.780
must be ready for falls,
for sacrifice, for mistakes.

01:16:41.540 --> 01:16:44.100
You shouldn’t be afraid
to make mistakes,

01:16:44.340 --> 01:16:47.620
because you’ll certainly
make a lot of them.

01:16:47.820 --> 01:16:50.020
You said it well.

01:16:51.100 --> 01:16:54.820
For me, individual sports
are harder.

01:16:57.100 --> 01:17:00.820
If it were easy,
everyone would do it.

01:17:01.540 --> 01:17:06.276
As Steffi Graf says, you can’t
succeed if you haven’t fallen.

01:17:06.940 --> 01:17:08.900
That’s how it is.

01:17:10.140 --> 01:17:14.780
Once again, thank you
for this long conversation.

01:17:15.037 --> 01:17:17.677
Just tell me one more thing.

01:17:17.870 --> 01:17:21.466
Some of my fans
from WBA asked me,

01:17:21.606 --> 01:17:24.934
even though you already
told me once, "Why WBA?"

01:17:25.214 --> 01:17:28.334
That’s a crazy story.

01:17:28.700 --> 01:17:39.912
My good friend, a journalist,
how they root for theis clubs...

01:17:40.170 --> 01:17:43.137
and that’s a whole other level.

01:17:45.740 --> 01:17:55.673
It was 2003 or 2004...
WBA was losing games...

01:17:57.119 --> 01:18:03.126
We were at a tournament,
he was watching them, crying.

01:18:03.960 --> 01:18:09.257
I wondered what was wrong
with him, he was shaking.

01:18:10.375 --> 01:18:13.182
So I started watching it with him.

01:18:13.671 --> 01:18:20.281
Since then, I’ve been
rooting for WBA with him.

01:18:22.660 --> 01:18:27.500
He’s a journalist of course,
always at the club.

01:18:28.340 --> 01:18:34.980
They invited me too.
It’s not easy being a fan.

01:18:36.220 --> 01:18:43.850
We’re always up and down,
like a yo-yo.

01:18:45.780 --> 01:18:50.881
But once you start,
you can’t stop.

01:18:51.028 --> 01:18:53.850
Then you’re eternal.
Even you came...

01:18:53.981 --> 01:18:58.694
Akrobinović said:
"We have to go, we have to go..."

01:18:59.580 --> 01:19:03.381
Unfortunately, there’s never
enough time.

01:19:03.579 --> 01:19:05.539
Everything goes by so fast.

01:19:06.380 --> 01:19:16.140
But since 2003-2004,
I’ve been their fan. -Bravo!

01:19:17.360 --> 01:19:19.103
Thank you. It’s my pleasure.
-Thank you.

